dismissalText.commentary: Younis Khan run out (Waller/†Taibu) 78 (72b 9x4 0x6 86m) SR: 108.33

dismissalComment.html: Has Younis run himself out? Yes he has . This is hit wide of deep midwicket, and Younis stutters before starting for the second. Waller's throw is flat and quick, and even a dive from Younis is not good enough. They didn't run the first one fast, and were never too keen on the second until -without a hint of disagreement - they both decided to go for the second. Younis had just survived a plumb lbw call in the last over

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

dismissalText.commentary: Misbah-ul-Haq lbw b Price 54 (64b 3x4 1x6 96m) SR: 84.37

dismissalComment.html: Misbah has one of his famous brain freeze movements. Tries the reverse sweep. Not the subtle one where you change the bat face at the last movement. He jumps across the crease, almost as if playing a switch hit, and then changes stance. Price bowls full and straight, beats the bat, and hits him dead in front

dismissalText.commentary: Shoaib Malik c †Taibu b Chigumbura 2 (5b 0x4 0x6 12m) SR: 40

dismissalComment.html: Taibu has pulled off a blinder, and another comeback man has failed! This will rad as a wicket for the bowler, but it is all down to Taibu. He saw this ball sliding down leg, and moved exceptionally early in anticipation. Malik got a thick edge down the leg side, and Taibu flew across to his left to pouch this one-handed. Smart and athletic both at the same time

dismissalText.long: c Sohail Tanvir b Aizaz Cheema
dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor c Sohail Tanvir b Aizaz Cheema 84 (103b 7x4 0x6 159m) SR: 81.55

dismissalComment.html: Cheema strikes! What a time for the deutant to take this wicket! Taylor has left Zimbabwe 200 metres short of finishing this half-marathon. This is a length ball again, Taylor looks to slog it, but it perhaps surprised by the quickness of it off the surface. Top-edges. Tanvir runs to his left from midwicket to complete a simple catch. Over to you Elton

dismissalText.commentary: Vusi Sibanda c & b Aizaz Cheema 73 (89b 6x4 2x6 117m) SR: 82.02

dismissalComment.html: What a way to go! Sibanda is caught-and-bowled and bat-pad! To the insult he has added an injury! He gives this length ball some humpty, and the thick inside edge hits his back pad, and it lobs off to Cheema who delightfully completes a simple catch. Sibanda is on the ground, that ball might have hit his knee. He has to be helped off the pitch. The medical support carry his gloves and pads for him as he hobbles off

Hafeez! Hafeez looks innocuous when compared to Ajmal, but he is also getting them wickets! Masakadza moves too far across and tries to play this offbreak square as opposed to down the ground. dismissalText.commentary: Chamu Chibhabha b Sohail Tanvir 1 (7b 0x4 0x6 10m) SR: 14.28

dismissalComment.html: Too good. Simply too good. Can't do too much about these deliveries. Would have got some of the greats of the game out. He goes wide of the crease, pitches this short of a length, on middle and off, Chibhabha plays the angle, and then the off-cut comes into the play. It moves away slightly, hits the top of off. Just doff your hat, and walk off, Justice

dismissalText.commentary: Elton Chigumbura run out (Umar Akmal/†Adnan Akmal) 24 (23b 2x4 0x6 35m) SR: 104.34

dismissalComment.html: another low full toss, and Chigumbura goes down the ground. The mis-hit lands short of long-off, Umar Akmal fumbles there, but makes up for it with a flat throw at the striker's end to get Chigumbura out

image.caption: Ray Price
image.longCaption: Ray Price portrait, World Cup 2011, February 11, 2011

commentTextItems.html: He has taken guard at sixth stump outside off, he is going to slog it to leg. Gets the length ball too, but can't time it well enough to clear the midwicket boundary. Heartbreak for Zimbabwe, bullet bitten by Pakistan

commentPostTextItems.html: Thank you everybody for joining us. The mathematicians, the brothers living in England and El Salvador, the Pashto speakers, the Punjabis, the Ndebele speakers, and everybody else, it was a superb game of cricket. This Sidharth Monga singing off. So long, and thanks for all the fish

Time for presentation. The Man of the Match is Younis Khan. He says, "At that time we had lost a quick wicket, suddenly me and Hafeez said we needed to bat till 20 overs at least. I was lucky I got early boundaries. It was a misjudgement to get out. The pitch was quite good, it slowed down later. I told Hafeez, 'You are playing like me and I am playing like you.'"

Misbah-ul-Haq says, "We were 20-30 runs short. On crucial stages, we kept losing wickets. That's why they restricted us. Ajmal is our main weapon, especially on the slow tracks, but the pacers did a great job. Tanvir with the new ball, Cheema in the middle overs, and Junaid, who was disappointing at start, came back well in the final over."

Brendan Taylor, who brought Zimbabwe so close but looks pretty down now, says, "We let is slip in that second-last over. Credit to Pakistan, they held their nerve a little bit better than us. over all a pretty good game. We will hold our heads high, and take positives. Me not getting out would have been nice. Vusi was also going nice. But it's the game of cricket for you. Credit to them."

Zimbabwe are in a state of shock. Pakistan quietly smile and shake hands. They know they were run close. What a game we have had. With the bat Pakistan hared out of the blocks, but Zimbabwe kept pulling them back. Sibanda and Taylor then absorbed the pressure, and took their side agonisingly close. Pakistan lost the plot a bit in the end, especially when Sohail Tanvir bowled three poor overs in the Powerplay. Then two inexperienced bowlers, Cheema and Junaid, somehow managed to win Pakistan the match

commentPostTextItems.html: Stunned silence in Bulawayo as Pakistan have all but won this one. Junaid has done well under pressure. He has not given them length to get under. Can Utseya hit a six off the last ball?

commentTextItems.html: another full toss, Lamb hits it square, but finds point, Six feet either side, and he would have got four
another low full toss, Elton can't get under it, gets just the single to cover. Applause from Pakistan's support staff
low full toss, Chigumbura goes across its line, looking for the biog slog, doesn't connect at all. Advantage Pakistan

commentPreTextItems.html: Another five-man conference. Junaid will bowl the last over. Keegan Meth watches on from the sidelines. Junaid stretches before he runs in to bowl. Round the stumps he goes

commentTextItems.html: full toss outside off, driven with an open face, wide of deep cover, gets two runs, keeps the strike

commentPreTextItems.html: Thirteen off 7. What does Chigumbura do? Go for four or one?

commentTextItems.html: he goes for the single, steering this widish delivery to third man

commentPreTextItems.html: Greg Lamb is the new man in, but Chigumbura is on strike

commentTextItems.html: why is he bowling length? Heaved away all along the ground, but Malik from deep midwicket runs to his right and makes a desperate lunge to keep this from reaching the boundary. Could this be a match-winning lunge?

length again, another slower ball, and Taylor has swept it in front of square. Malik does well at deep midwicket, but can't keep them from taking the second.
slower ball, length again, and Chigumbura goes after it again, the mis-hit lands short of deep cover

commentPreTextItems.html: Tension all around. Pakistan having a five-man conference. Cheema will bowl the 49th over. Who will bowl the last? Junaid Khan? ZXimbabwe will back themselves. Cheema, on debut, aged 32. To bowl a very important over

commentTextItems.html: bowls length ball first up, and Chigumbura has absolutely slapped it across its face. Powerful swipe past cover. No fielder moved. Neither long-off nor cover had a chance
the regulation offbreak, Taylor tries the sweep, is beaten by the extra bounce

commentPostTextItems.html: Just three off the over, but no wickets taken. Ajmal has left the game in balance still

sweeps this one powerfully, this just held its line, and he keeps the sweep down, gets a single to fine leg
another doosra, Taylor jumps out of the crease, and pads this away
doosra, Taylor tries to loft this over leg, is beaten because he is playing for the offbreak

commentPreTextItems.html: Powerplay over. Twenty-rive required off 18. What a match. Ajmal to bowl his last over. This over could decide the game

commentTextItems.html: sharp offbreak, guides past point for a single
near run-out, full on the pads, hit straight to midwicket, sends Chigumbura back who is so far up the pitch he gives up. The throw misses, though

dismissalText.commentary: Younis Khan run out (Waller/†Taibu) 78 (72b 9x4 0x6 86m) SR: 108.33

dismissalComment.html: Has Younis run himself out? Yes he has . This is hit wide of deep midwicket, and Younis stutters before starting for the second. Waller's throw is flat and quick, and even a dive from Younis is not good enough. They didn't run the first one fast, and were never too keen on the second until -without a hint of disagreement - they both decided to go for the second. Younis had just survived a plumb lbw call in the last over

dismissalText.commentary: Adnan Akmal c Mpofu b Price 27 (32b 2x4 0x6 42m) SR: 84.37

dismissalComment.html: tries the trusted big reverse-sweep, Price stays full and straight, and he top-edges this low full toss to point. Second wicket for Price, both off reverse-sweeps. Says something about him: he makes you do these low-percentage things

dismissalText.commentary: Vusi Sibanda c & b Aizaz Cheema 73 (89b 6x4 2x6 117m) SR: 82.02

dismissalComment.html: What a way to go! Sibanda is caught-and-bowled and bat-pad! To the insult he has added an injury! He gives this length ball some humpty, and the thick inside edge hits his back pad, and it lobs off to Cheema who delightfully completes a simple catch. Sibanda is on the ground, that ball might have hit his knee. He has to be helped off the pitch. The medical support carry his gloves and pads for him as he hobbles off

headshotImage.caption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Chamu Chibhabha b Sohail Tanvir 1 (7b 0x4 0x6 10m) SR: 14.28

dismissalComment.html: Too good. Simply too good. Can't do too much about these deliveries. Would have got some of the greats of the game out. He goes wide of the crease, pitches this short of a length, on middle and off, Chibhabha plays the angle, and then the off-cut comes into the play. It moves away slightly, hits the top of off. Just doff your hat, and walk off, Justice

dismissalText.commentary: Hamilton Masakadza lbw b Mohammad Hafeez 15 (27b 2x4 0x6 49m) SR: 55.55

dismissalComment.html: Hafeez! Hafeez looks innocuous when compared to Ajmal, but he is also getting them wickets! Masakadza moves too far across and tries to play this offbreak square as opposed to down the ground. Misses, and is hit in front of middle. Anybody's guess if this would have hit leg, but by moving across and looking to play across the line, he has made it look much worse

headshotImage.caption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Sohail Tanvir player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.long: c Sohail Tanvir b Aizaz Cheema
dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor c Sohail Tanvir b Aizaz Cheema 84 (103b 7x4 0x6 159m) SR: 81.55

dismissalComment.html: Cheema strikes! What a time for the deutant to take this wicket! Taylor has left Zimbabwe 200 metres short of finishing this half-marathon. This is a length ball again, Taylor looks to slog it, but it perhaps surprised by the quickness of it off the surface. Top-edges. Tanvir runs to his left from midwicket to complete a simple catch. Over to you Elton
